  title="Burnout Is Not Depression (But They Look Alike) | Maren Voss, LMFT"
  description="Burnout and depression share symptoms but require different treatment. How to tell the difference and what actually helps."
  postTitle="Burnout Is Not Depression (But They Look a Lot Alike)"
  date="September 2025"
>
  <p>A client sits across from me and says: &ldquo;My doctor wants to put me on antidepressants. I think I might be depressed. But I&rsquo;m not sure that&rsquo;s what this is.&rdquo;</p>

  <p>I hear some version of this regularly, especially from people in demanding professional environments. They&rsquo;re exhausted. They&rsquo;re cynical. They&rsquo;ve lost the ability to care about things they used to care about. They meet the criteria for depression on a screening questionnaire, and they&rsquo;re not wrong. On paper, it looks like depression.</p>

  <p>But when we dig in, a different picture emerges.</p>

  <p><strong>Burnout and depression share symptoms:</strong> fatigue, loss of motivation, difficulty concentrating, irritability, sleep disruption, emotional flatness. The overlap is significant enough that burnout is frequently misdiagnosed as depression, even by competent clinicians.</p>

  <p><strong>The distinction matters because the treatment is different.</strong></p>

  <p>Depression, in the clinical sense, is a mood disorder. It can emerge without a clear external cause and often responds to a combination of medication and therapy that targets cognitive patterns, behavioral activation, and underlying vulnerability.</p>

  <p>Burnout is a response to sustained, unresolvable stress in a specific context, usually work, but also caregiving, graduate school, or any role where the demands consistently exceed your resources and you have limited control over the situation. Burnout is contextual. Remove the context (or change your relationship to it), and the symptoms improve.</p>

  <p>Here&rsquo;s the problem: telling a burned-out person to take an SSRI and practice self-care is treating the symptom, not the cause. The antidepressant might take the edge off the emotional flatness, and the self-care might create temporary relief. But if the underlying conditions haven&rsquo;t changed, the burnout comes back.</p>

  <p><strong>What actually helps with burnout:</strong></p>

  <p>The first step is recognition. Many high-achievers resist the burnout label because it feels like admitting weakness. It&rsquo;s not. It&rsquo;s admitting that you&rsquo;re human and that the system you&rsquo;re operating in is unsustainable. Those are different things.</p>

  <p>The second step is understanding what&rsquo;s keeping you in it. This is where therapy gets interesting. Because for many people, the answer isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t leave&rdquo; but rather &ldquo;something in me won&rsquo;t let me stop.&rdquo; That something is usually a belief or a pattern that was installed long before this job, and it&rsquo;s been running quietly underneath your entire career.</p>

  <p>EMDR and parts work are effective here because they can reach the underlying drivers of the burnout cycle: the belief that your worth equals your output, the fear that slowing down means being left behind, the childhood experience that taught you rest has to be earned.</p>

  <p><strong>This isn&rsquo;t about quitting your job.</strong> Some of my clients do make major career changes. Others stay in the same role but relate to it completely differently once the underlying pattern has been addressed. The point isn&rsquo;t to escape the context. It&rsquo;s to stop being run by an unconscious program that won&rsquo;t let you take care of yourself.</p>

  <p>If you&rsquo;re not sure whether what you&rsquo;re experiencing is burnout or depression, a conversation with a therapist who understands the distinction can help you figure it out. <a href="/contact" class="text-link-light">Schedule a consultation</a>.</p>
